WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.420
Hi, everybody. Thank you for joining us.

2
00:00:04.940 --> 00:00:08.800
Today, we're going to have a session on the

3
00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:12.720
flip side of the benefit of immunotherapy for

4
00:00:12.760 --> 00:00:16.310
cancer, which is the side effects from that

5
00:00:17.060 --> 00:00:20.520
therapy. So these are the so-called

6
00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:22.580
immune-related adverse events.

7
00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:26.730
They can affect any organ system in the body, and

8
00:00:26.780 --> 00:00:30.020
we have numerous examples at this point.

9
00:00:30.420 --> 00:00:34.210
Literally, any tissue can become inflamed in someone who's receiving

10
00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:38.100
immunotherapy for cancer. The most common tissues actually

11
00:00:38.140 --> 00:00:40.180
fall into some general categories.

12
00:00:40.190 --> 00:00:44.080
So barrier tissues like the skin, the gut,

13
00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:48.380
and the lungs are very frequent targets of these immune-related

14
00:00:48.460 --> 00:00:52.440
adverse events. And then endocrine organs, the

15
00:00:52.460 --> 00:00:56.110
most common being the thyroid gland, but every endocrine organ has also been

16
00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:57.180
described as a target.

17
00:00:58.830 --> 00:01:00.920
The most common

18
00:01:00.930 --> 00:01:05.960
severe

19
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.900
immune-related adverse event is colitis or inflammatory

20
00:01:09.940 --> 00:01:13.620
toxicities in the gut. I mention that because that is going to be a

21
00:01:13.700 --> 00:01:17.500
theme that runs through a lot of today's talks.

22
00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:22.620
My talk will start. I'm going to do a little bit of an overview of what we

23
00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:26.140
know about immune-related adverse events in the colon in

24
00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:30.220
humans, and then the following two speakers are going to

25
00:01:30.260 --> 00:01:33.700
talk about an area in this research that really is

26
00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:37.740
extremely important and still really at the beginning, which is

27
00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:40.320
mouse models of immune-related adverse events.

28
00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:44.060
The field has really been held back by our

29
00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:47.900
inability to study in detail the

30
00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:50.070
mechanisms that are driving these toxicities.

31
00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:54.560
And we have a lot of technologies to start to study this in humans, but when we

32
00:01:54.600 --> 00:01:58.040
come up with hypotheses, it can be very hard to test them.

33
00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:02.050
And many people have tried to study these toxicities

34
00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:06.000
in mice. The two speakers today have, in my

35
00:02:06.040 --> 00:02:09.741
opinion, really brought this field to the point where we

36
00:02:09.820 --> 00:02:13.520
can actually start to learn something from our animal models.

37
00:02:15.540 --> 00:02:18.470
So with that, we'll move on to

38
00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:20.460
our first

39
00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:21.960
talk.

40
00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:23.400
Maybe.

41
00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:26.360
Oh, sorry about that.

42
00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:32.660
And I'm going to be talking about the differences

43
00:02:33.220 --> 00:02:37.020
between CTLA-4 and PD-1 colitis.

44
00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:39.620
These are my disclosures.

45
00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:42.380
And can we start the timer?

46
00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:45.480
Thank you. So

47
00:02:46.300 --> 00:02:50.140
immune-related adverse events, as I mentioned, are a side effect of immunotherapy

48
00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:53.500
for cancer, but they're more than just a side effect.

49
00:02:53.560 --> 00:02:57.470
They're a model for understanding fundamental mechanisms of

50
00:02:57.520 --> 00:03:01.200
immune regulation in humans. And what I mean by

51
00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.100
that is that these toxicities, when

52
00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:05.320
we

53
00:03:06.180 --> 00:03:09.160
block PD-1 or CTLA-4, the

54
00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:12.660
toxicities are the phenotype of receptor loss.

55
00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:17.220
And so they give us a window into what those pathways were doing in

56
00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:20.380
that patient in the moments before they had treatment.

57
00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:24.420
I think this is important for understanding fundamental mechanism,

58
00:03:24.460 --> 00:03:27.820
again, of immune regulation. It's also an opportunity to

59
00:03:27.860 --> 00:03:31.340
understand the first steps in autoimmune disease.

60
00:03:31.940 --> 00:03:35.670
And these inflammatory reactions are not the same as

61
00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:39.640
autoimmune diseases, but they have many things in common, and we

62
00:03:39.680 --> 00:03:41.940
have the ability to watch them unfold.

63
00:03:42.020 --> 00:03:45.880
We know exactly what the immune perturbation is, we know exactly when it

64
00:03:45.940 --> 00:03:49.790
occurred, and so we can study each step in

65
00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:53.500
that process. And so I think of them as a human

66
00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:55.880
model of the human diseases that we care about.

67
00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:59.769
Again, not exactly the same thing as those diseases, but potential

68
00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:03.320
insights into what the earliest stages of inflammatory disease looks like.

69
00:04:04.580 --> 00:04:08.380
In addition to being, I think, fundamentally interesting from a

70
00:04:08.420 --> 00:04:12.220
scientific perspective, they're also a really complicated clinical problem.

71
00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:16.280
Why is that? Well, we're trying to minimize morbidity and mortality from

72
00:04:16.300 --> 00:04:20.140
these toxicities at the same time that we're balancing the protective

73
00:04:20.180 --> 00:04:23.090
effect of immunotherapy against the cancer.

74
00:04:23.469 --> 00:04:27.230
And getting that balance right is really tricky, especially when you

75
00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:31.280
don't know what the mechanisms are driving the toxicities.

76
00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:34.920
We've learned a lot about the mechanisms that govern immunotherapy

77
00:04:34.940 --> 00:04:35.540
response.

78
00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:39.660
But it was with that goal in mind that got me studying

79
00:04:40.340 --> 00:04:44.240
immune checkpoint inhibitor colitis or CPI colitis, as it's here.

80
00:04:45.020 --> 00:04:48.600
And the experiment we did was to take three groups of

81
00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:51.880
patients and take biopsies from their colon.

82
00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:55.800
The populations that we studied are going to be color-coded in the next set of

83
00:04:55.860 --> 00:04:59.790
slides. So in green, we have healthy controls, gray are a

84
00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:03.290
different kind of control, people on immunotherapy who did not have

85
00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:06.420
colitis, and then yellow are the patients who had

86
00:05:06.460 --> 00:05:08.510
colitis from immunotherapy.

87
00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:12.720
And we studied these biopsies by multi-spectral flow

88
00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:15.850
cytometry and single-cell RNA sequencing.

89
00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:18.880
And a few things I want to point out about this cohort of 24 patients.

90
00:05:19.140 --> 00:05:23.040
First, almost all of them received dual checkpoint blockades, CTLA-4 and

91
00:05:23.120 --> 00:05:26.780
PD-1 inhibition, but a couple of them did get

92
00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:30.860
CTLA-4 blockade alone. These patients were biopsied within

93
00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:34.720
days of onset of symptoms. One patient was actually biopsied on the day they

94
00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:38.720
first had symptoms. Only one patient in the entire cohort had steroids

95
00:05:38.740 --> 00:05:42.630
before the biopsy. So we're really looking at the earliest stages of what is

96
00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:44.940
going on without any other immune manipulation.

97
00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:48.940
You may be wondering, where did those gray patients come from?

98
00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.980
So those are people who had symptoms suggestive of ICI

99
00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:56.100
colitis, who ultimately didn't have it on biopsy.

100
00:05:56.110 --> 00:06:00.100
And they fall into two groups. Half of them had inflammation in the upper GI tract

101
00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:03.460
alone, and half of them had no inflammation anywhere in their GI

102
00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:07.352
tract.And I'm not going to show you any of this data really today,

103
00:06:07.712 --> 00:06:11.532
so I'm just going to say it, that if you look at the gray controls and the green

104
00:06:11.572 --> 00:06:15.362
controls by many, many different measures, we were unable to find any

105
00:06:15.492 --> 00:06:17.352
differences between those two populations.

106
00:06:18.972 --> 00:06:22.852
So what did we find? Well, as you would expect, these are CD45

107
00:06:23.592 --> 00:06:27.332
cells, unbiased clustering. We found all the

108
00:06:27.372 --> 00:06:30.612
populations you would expect to find in immune cells in the colon.

109
00:06:31.652 --> 00:06:35.352
And if we group those cells by where they came

110
00:06:35.432 --> 00:06:39.212
from, you can see that there are two populations that really are

111
00:06:39.292 --> 00:06:42.812
all yellow from patients with colitis. So what are those cells?

112
00:06:42.952 --> 00:06:46.862
Those are cytotoxic cells, high levels of activation markers, making

113
00:06:46.892 --> 00:06:48.702
interferon gamma and proliferating.

114
00:06:50.572 --> 00:06:54.452
If we dive down into sub-clustering, look at the CD8 T cells alone, we see the

115
00:06:54.472 --> 00:06:57.892
same thing. Cytotoxic effector cells, cycling T cells.

116
00:06:59.732 --> 00:07:03.172
If we look at the CD4 T cells, we see again something that's very similar.

117
00:07:03.732 --> 00:07:07.172
We see Th1 effector cells that are making interferon gamma and a smaller

118
00:07:07.212 --> 00:07:10.622
population of cycling cells. We were

119
00:07:10.652 --> 00:07:14.012
interested in figuring out what the origin of these

120
00:07:14.032 --> 00:07:17.852
colitis-associated cells was. And the way that we decided to do this was to

121
00:07:17.912 --> 00:07:21.892
take advantage of the fact that a T cell receptor is a molecular

122
00:07:22.152 --> 00:07:25.352
barcode identifying clonally related T cells.

123
00:07:25.812 --> 00:07:29.412
Every clonotype of T cell has the same T cell receptor.

124
00:07:29.452 --> 00:07:32.752
It's genetically encoded, and so we can determine

125
00:07:32.792 --> 00:07:36.152
relationships between T cells even if they have different

126
00:07:36.172 --> 00:07:36.832
phenotypes.

127
00:07:37.752 --> 00:07:41.732
And so this is a little bit of a difficult plot to look at,

128
00:07:41.792 --> 00:07:42.652
so I'm going to walk you through it.

129
00:07:42.692 --> 00:07:46.352
If we just focus on the controls over here because it's easiest, what we have on

130
00:07:46.392 --> 00:07:49.952
the X and Y axis is each of the eight populations that we found

131
00:07:50.092 --> 00:07:53.732
in the CD8 compartment. And if you take

132
00:07:54.072 --> 00:07:57.492
this box here that says 86, that's 86

133
00:07:57.512 --> 00:08:00.472
clonotypes of T cell that are overlapping

134
00:08:00.512 --> 00:08:04.012
between column one and column two.

135
00:08:04.392 --> 00:08:07.552
So what are those? Resident memory cells in the

136
00:08:07.592 --> 00:08:11.072
interepithelial space and resident memory cells in the lamina propria.

137
00:08:11.612 --> 00:08:15.121
So this is telling us that clonotypes found in those

138
00:08:15.192 --> 00:08:18.712
two phenotypic compartments are actually related to each

139
00:08:18.772 --> 00:08:22.612
other. Makes sense. In a healthy person, T cells can go back and

140
00:08:22.672 --> 00:08:26.612
forth between the lamina propria and the interepithelial space.

141
00:08:27.532 --> 00:08:31.412
We see the same thing in the no colitis patients as exposed to immunotherapy.

142
00:08:32.432 --> 00:08:35.952
One of the many pieces of data that those populations are really the same and

143
00:08:35.992 --> 00:08:37.632
something very different in colitis.

144
00:08:38.592 --> 00:08:42.112
So we should focus first on the red because that's the easiest to understand.

145
00:08:42.773 --> 00:08:46.172
Red is the two different colitis associated populations, the

146
00:08:46.212 --> 00:08:48.532
cytotoxic cells and the proliferating cells.

147
00:08:48.652 --> 00:08:52.072
And it's saying there's a tremendous amount of overlap between those two

148
00:08:52.132 --> 00:08:53.952
populations. Again, it makes sense.

149
00:08:54.032 --> 00:08:57.732
The cells that are activated and cytotoxic are the very

150
00:08:57.852 --> 00:08:59.441
same cells that are proliferating.

151
00:09:00.272 --> 00:09:03.212
What we did not expect to find was what we see here in yellow.

152
00:09:03.592 --> 00:09:07.012
So those are clonotypes that are shared between

153
00:09:07.022 --> 00:09:10.712
the resident memory cells and the colitis

154
00:09:10.772 --> 00:09:14.062
associated cells, implying that the resident memory

155
00:09:14.292 --> 00:09:18.272
pool is actually responsible for contributing all of

156
00:09:18.312 --> 00:09:21.852
those colitis associated cells, or the cause of

157
00:09:21.872 --> 00:09:25.212
colitis is activation of resident memory cells.

158
00:09:25.232 --> 00:09:29.162
So I'm not showing you all the data that led up to this drawing, but the model that

159
00:09:29.192 --> 00:09:33.172
we have is that at baseline, we have many resident

160
00:09:33.212 --> 00:09:37.152
memory T cells in the colon. In fact, in many organs, particularly the barrier

161
00:09:37.272 --> 00:09:37.652
organs.

162
00:09:38.512 --> 00:09:42.252
When patients get immunotherapy, some of them have

163
00:09:42.372 --> 00:09:45.312
reactivation of that resident memory pool.

164
00:09:45.912 --> 00:09:49.252
Those cells start producing granzyme. They produce interferon gamma.

165
00:09:49.272 --> 00:09:52.792
The interferon gamma acts on the tissue, but it also acts on macrophages.

166
00:09:52.812 --> 00:09:56.071
Data I'm not showing you. Those macrophages become activated.

167
00:09:56.092 --> 00:09:59.992
They secrete inflammatory cytokines and also chemokines,

168
00:10:00.032 --> 00:10:03.212
which call in additional immune cells from the blood,

169
00:10:03.952 --> 00:10:05.892
probably perpetuating the colitis.

170
00:10:06.692 --> 00:10:09.772
And then something's going on with those regulatory T cells.

171
00:10:09.812 --> 00:10:12.912
And we had a little bit of data from this initial experiment, but that was one of

172
00:10:12.952 --> 00:10:15.872
our open questions. What's happening to the regulatory T cells?

173
00:10:16.772 --> 00:10:16.932
So

174
00:10:18.072 --> 00:10:21.941
we had an idea that there may be some loss of regulatory T cells,

175
00:10:21.992 --> 00:10:25.272
and so our question was, are they actually depleted

176
00:10:25.292 --> 00:10:28.612
by the CTLA-4 antibodies? Why did we wonder that?

177
00:10:29.152 --> 00:10:32.612
Well, there are actually a number of publications that have shown this in mice, and

178
00:10:32.632 --> 00:10:35.012
I'm showing you the first one here.

179
00:10:35.072 --> 00:10:38.992
And what has been found is that mice who

180
00:10:39.032 --> 00:10:42.932
are treated with CTLA-4 blocking antibodies actually have rapid

181
00:10:42.952 --> 00:10:46.422
depletion of their regulatory T cells from their tumors.

182
00:10:46.732 --> 00:10:50.232
This is one piece of data in the paper. This is a B16 melanoma model.

183
00:10:50.732 --> 00:10:54.712
The mice have been given CD4 T cells that are specific for the

184
00:10:54.732 --> 00:10:58.472
tumor, and you can see that in untreated animals, many of those CD4 T

185
00:10:58.552 --> 00:11:02.292
cells differentiate into Tregs. If you give CTLA-4

186
00:11:02.332 --> 00:11:05.172
antibodies, that Treg population vanishes.

187
00:11:05.852 --> 00:11:08.892
And again, they're able to show that this is through

188
00:11:09.372 --> 00:11:13.232
loss of the regulatory T cells. This is one

189
00:11:13.292 --> 00:11:15.532
of their most compelling pieces of data.

190
00:11:15.612 --> 00:11:18.512
Here, they've looked at the effect of immunotherapy

191
00:11:19.132 --> 00:11:22.752
when the Fc gamma RII receptors were removed from the

192
00:11:22.772 --> 00:11:26.352
mouse's genome. And what they find is that the therapeutic benefit of

193
00:11:26.392 --> 00:11:30.322
immunotherapy vanishes. So their conclusion from this is that

194
00:11:30.532 --> 00:11:33.932
you need to be able to deplete regulatory T cells for

195
00:11:34.012 --> 00:11:36.412
CTLA-4 antibodies to be effective in mice.

196
00:11:37.232 --> 00:11:39.492
Again, multiple other groups have shown this at this point.

197
00:11:40.352 --> 00:11:43.572
So we wondered if that was happening in our patients.

198
00:11:44.052 --> 00:11:48.032
And those are the Tregs. And you can see just from coloring, there are many Tregs

199
00:11:48.072 --> 00:11:49.692
in the colitis patients.

200
00:11:50.532 --> 00:11:54.512
If you look at total counts by flow cytometry, you actually see more regulatory T

201
00:11:54.612 --> 00:11:58.522
cells. They have the same percentage CTLA-4 positive, and

202
00:11:58.552 --> 00:12:01.292
they also have the same amount of CTLA-4 on their surface.

203
00:12:02.812 --> 00:12:06.532
And I'll just remind you, these are samples taken very early on in the

204
00:12:06.552 --> 00:12:10.440
colitis course.Suggesting that we're not really looking

205
00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:14.080
too late. This is probably something still very early on in the process.

206
00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:18.580
It's certainly possible, though, that we missed something happening in a regulatory

207
00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:19.440
T cell subset.

208
00:12:20.460 --> 00:12:24.040
So we put some thought into how could we actually probe this

209
00:12:24.080 --> 00:12:27.600
question and we would expect if CTLA-4

210
00:12:27.660 --> 00:12:31.180
antibodies are depleting regulatory T cells, the mechanism is

211
00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:35.140
antibody binding to Treg, and then either NK cells or macrophages are

212
00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.900
killing those Tregs. That should require the

213
00:12:38.920 --> 00:12:42.860
CTLA-4 antibody. And so if we compare CTLA-4

214
00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.790
colitis to PD-1 colitis, we may be able to see a difference

215
00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:49.140
that will suggest that the CTLA-4 antibodies are depleting.

216
00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:53.600
We didn't have enough data to do that in the initial experiment, so that's where

217
00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:56.680
Lily Orgler came in. She's a post-doc in my lab.

218
00:12:56.820 --> 00:13:00.480
And what Lily did was to take two published data sets, our

219
00:13:00.520 --> 00:13:04.460
initial one, one that we contributed to a few years later, and then added

220
00:13:04.470 --> 00:13:08.100
a bunch of additional PD-1 colitis cells to that

221
00:13:08.110 --> 00:13:12.020
analysis. So we ended up with 230,000 cells where we

222
00:13:12.060 --> 00:13:13.379
could actually do this comparison.

223
00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:16.690
And this is the initial UMAP from that

224
00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:20.840
combination analysis. Lily found, again, the same populations of cells

225
00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.560
we were expecting to find. And at this high level, we found a

226
00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:27.940
few general things. We found slightly

227
00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:31.900
more CD8 T cells. Those are the dark blue lines in the

228
00:13:31.920 --> 00:13:35.620
colitis patients. It is statistically significant, but it is a very

229
00:13:35.700 --> 00:13:38.260
small overall effect on CD8 T cells.

230
00:13:38.670 --> 00:13:42.630
And then there's a slight increase in the number of cycling cells that

231
00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:46.580
we see. That's what we see in this dark red, and you can see there are a

232
00:13:46.620 --> 00:13:49.000
few more of those bars. So high level,

233
00:13:50.180 --> 00:13:50.960
small changes.

234
00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:55.520
If we compare CTLA-4 and PD-1 colitis, we see no difference

235
00:13:56.500 --> 00:13:57.920
again, at this high level.

236
00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:02.900
So we then went and looked at CD4 T cells

237
00:14:04.480 --> 00:14:06.120
in more detail by sub-clustering.

238
00:14:06.400 --> 00:14:09.880
We identified 12 distinct populations of CD4 T cells.

239
00:14:11.320 --> 00:14:14.570
And if you look here, you might not be able to read the labels, but you can see the

240
00:14:14.660 --> 00:14:18.640
colors. Colitis has a lot more red, and obviously we colored

241
00:14:18.660 --> 00:14:21.960
that on purpose. So the light pink are the

242
00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:25.520
cytotoxic TH1, TH17 cells,

243
00:14:25.880 --> 00:14:29.450
the dark pink are the Tregs, and then

244
00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.880
the dark red at the bottom are the cycling cells.

245
00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:35.170
And again, you can see it really looks like there are a lot more of all three of

246
00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:38.980
those populations in colitis, and indeed, we do see that statistically.

247
00:14:39.740 --> 00:14:43.120
In truth, we see statistical differences across all of these populations.

248
00:14:43.420 --> 00:14:43.920
Most of them,

249
00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:46.840
to me, do not seem like they're very meaningful.

250
00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:50.380
The big differences really are in those populations that I highlighted.

251
00:14:51.740 --> 00:14:55.329
And again, when we compare dual colitis CTLA-4 PD-1

252
00:14:55.420 --> 00:14:59.290
blockade versus PD-1 colitis, we find no statistically significant differences,

253
00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:02.000
including in the regulatory T cells.

254
00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:06.280
We also looked at clonotypic expansion, and this was a big surprise to

255
00:15:06.340 --> 00:15:10.300
us. Across all of these different groups, there's no significant

256
00:15:10.340 --> 00:15:14.180
difference in the number of expanded clonotypes.

257
00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:17.620
There are just as many expanded clonotypes in a healthy

258
00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:20.400
person as there are in someone with colitis.

259
00:15:22.240 --> 00:15:25.360
So this is what that looks like if you just place it on a UMAP.

260
00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:29.190
All of the blue are expanded clonotypes, and you can see they

261
00:15:29.540 --> 00:15:33.480
represent many of the populations that we were able to

262
00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:36.760
identify. These are expanded resident cells.

263
00:15:36.920 --> 00:15:39.490
These are the activated effector cells.

264
00:15:39.530 --> 00:15:41.040
These are the proliferating cells.

265
00:15:43.080 --> 00:15:46.840
But if you compare colitis to the healthy controls, you do see a difference

266
00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:50.720
in which cells are expanded. So the expanded cells are largely the

267
00:15:50.760 --> 00:15:52.580
resident memory cells in healthy patients.

268
00:15:53.060 --> 00:15:56.440
In the colitis patients, it's really those effector cells and those

269
00:15:56.460 --> 00:15:57.380
proliferating cells.

270
00:15:58.230 --> 00:16:00.520
And we can look at this across each one of the groups.

271
00:16:00.980 --> 00:16:04.920
And so here, everything is down-sampled, so they're comparable to each other.

272
00:16:05.220 --> 00:16:09.040
And again, you can see in the two control groups, it's really in that resident

273
00:16:09.049 --> 00:16:10.970
memory population that you see expansion.

274
00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:15.180
In the colitis, it's really in these activated cells.

275
00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:19.120
And there's a lot more expansion in the CTLA-4 population than in

276
00:16:19.160 --> 00:16:19.820
the PD-1.

277
00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:24.739
If we look at this another way where you're looking at what cells are expanding,

278
00:16:25.179 --> 00:16:28.960
again, you can see the pink bars are really where most of the

279
00:16:28.980 --> 00:16:32.440
clonotypic expansion is occurring in CTLA-4 blockade

280
00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:33.000
colitis.

281
00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:38.760
Next question we had is are there specific Treg

282
00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:42.160
phenotypes in these samples? So

283
00:16:42.260 --> 00:16:46.080
we went in and we sub-clustered the regulatory

284
00:16:46.100 --> 00:16:49.660
T cells. And if you sub-cluster the regulatory T cells, we found 11 distinct

285
00:16:49.670 --> 00:16:53.520
populations. So there are different kinds of regulatory T

286
00:16:53.600 --> 00:16:54.880
cells here.

287
00:16:56.100 --> 00:16:59.010
And again, we find some that really do seem to be

288
00:16:59.940 --> 00:17:03.720
a little bit more preferentially expanded in the

289
00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:04.550
colitis patients.

290
00:17:05.620 --> 00:17:07.820
And in particular, we see these

291
00:17:07.980 --> 00:17:11.960
S1P1R positive regulatory T cells

292
00:17:11.980 --> 00:17:15.220
that seem to be quite expanded, as well as the cycling cells.

293
00:17:15.901 --> 00:17:18.240
It's not really the best way to look at these data, though.

294
00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:21.960
And the reason for that, at least in my opinion, is that we know the

295
00:17:22.060 --> 00:17:25.960
overall Tregs are expanded. So this is just looking at percentage

296
00:17:26.060 --> 00:17:29.460
of Tregs. I think a better way to look at this is percentage of

297
00:17:29.680 --> 00:17:33.300
CD4 positive cells. That gives you a good sense

298
00:17:33.400 --> 00:17:36.200
of what's actually happening, which is that over

299
00:17:37.220 --> 00:17:40.500
all of these populations, you're actually seeing some measure of expansion.

300
00:17:40.520 --> 00:17:44.280
There are more regulatory T cells compared to what you see in the

301
00:17:44.320 --> 00:17:48.040
healthy controls. There are some populations that are relatively

302
00:17:48.050 --> 00:17:48.610
expanding.

303
00:17:50.260 --> 00:17:52.820
This is showing that in a quantitative way, and you can see

304
00:17:53.640 --> 00:17:57.620
across the board, every Treg population that we identified

305
00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:00.400
is either increased in colitis or the same in colitis.

306
00:18:01.240 --> 00:18:04.700
And some of them are quite a bit more expanded.

307
00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:08.960
So then we finally get to that question that we had at the beginning.

308
00:18:09.340 --> 00:18:12.480
Do we see any difference in which

309
00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:16.220
populations expand if you compare CTLA-4

310
00:18:16.280 --> 00:18:20.264
blockade to PD-1 colitis?And the answer is

311
00:18:20.764 --> 00:18:24.504
sort of. So I'm only showing you the populations that

312
00:18:24.524 --> 00:18:28.324
differ. Almost everything that we look at is exactly the same between

313
00:18:28.364 --> 00:18:32.304
CTLA-4 colitis and PD-1 colitis. The differences are two

314
00:18:32.344 --> 00:18:35.663
populations. One are these naive Tregs, so no

315
00:18:36.964 --> 00:18:40.364
elevated activation markers. And what you can see there is

316
00:18:40.724 --> 00:18:44.664
that the CTLA-4 dual colitis has

317
00:18:44.704 --> 00:18:48.044
the same number of these naive cells as the two control populations.

318
00:18:48.724 --> 00:18:50.704
PD-1 colitis has an expansion of those.

319
00:18:50.824 --> 00:18:52.784
I honestly, at this point, don't know what to make of that.

320
00:18:52.804 --> 00:18:55.964
These are sort of hot-off-the-press kinds of data.

321
00:18:57.164 --> 00:18:58.694
The other population that changes are the

322
00:18:58.924 --> 00:19:02.584
S1PR1 positive

323
00:19:02.924 --> 00:19:06.564
regulatory T cells, cells that we think are migrating out of lymph

324
00:19:06.604 --> 00:19:10.574
nodes into the colon. And there we see a big

325
00:19:10.644 --> 00:19:14.354
expansion in CTLA-4 colitis that's really not present in

326
00:19:14.364 --> 00:19:17.444
PD-1 colitis, so a distinct phenotypic difference.

327
00:19:19.264 --> 00:19:22.124
What we didn't find were any populations that seem to be

328
00:19:22.144 --> 00:19:26.064
depleted in CTLA-4 colitis relative

329
00:19:26.104 --> 00:19:29.484
to PD-1 colitis or relative to the controls in this analysis.

330
00:19:31.484 --> 00:19:32.764
Again, these are

331
00:19:33.764 --> 00:19:37.624
biopsies that were taken from patients very

332
00:19:37.704 --> 00:19:41.664
soon after the onset of symptoms and only one patient

333
00:19:41.684 --> 00:19:45.304
in the entire cohort had steroids before the biopsies were taken.

334
00:19:45.344 --> 00:19:49.044
So this isn't sort of clouded by steroids or other kinds

335
00:19:49.134 --> 00:19:50.804
of colitis-associated treatments.

336
00:19:53.064 --> 00:19:56.924
Little bit more about this S1PR1 positive population,

337
00:19:56.964 --> 00:19:57.924
which again, we're still

338
00:19:58.784 --> 00:20:02.524
trying to study in more depth. These are also the cells that

339
00:20:03.564 --> 00:20:05.284
show the most clonotypic expansion.

340
00:20:05.624 --> 00:20:09.064
So that implies that there's something important about these cells.

341
00:20:09.134 --> 00:20:12.834
These cells are in some way responding to the colitis that's

342
00:20:12.884 --> 00:20:13.274
occurring.

343
00:20:14.224 --> 00:20:18.144
Whether they're having any beneficial effect in controlling the colitis is an open

344
00:20:18.184 --> 00:20:22.164
question, but they're clearly where the clonal expansion is occurring most.

345
00:20:23.884 --> 00:20:26.584
So that brings me to the conclusion for today.

346
00:20:27.284 --> 00:20:31.044
Points that I want to emphasize, both CTLA-4 and

347
00:20:31.104 --> 00:20:34.704
PD-1 colitis are characterized by an expansion of resident memory

348
00:20:34.724 --> 00:20:38.264
CD8 T cells. They really are the same in that category.

349
00:20:38.984 --> 00:20:42.824
Tregs are broadly expanded in CTLA-4 and PD-1 colitis.

350
00:20:43.684 --> 00:20:47.344
CTLA-4 antibodies do not deplete these Tregs

351
00:20:47.544 --> 00:20:49.384
from what we can tell in human colitis.

352
00:20:50.504 --> 00:20:53.624
CTLA-4 inhibitor colitis is characterized by an

353
00:20:53.644 --> 00:20:57.204
expansion of these TH1/TH17 effector cells.

354
00:20:57.524 --> 00:21:01.284
I'll tell you, we cannot separate those two phenotypes from each

355
00:21:01.324 --> 00:21:03.844
other, so the TH1 and TH17 are

356
00:21:04.724 --> 00:21:08.184
stuck clustered together. And then we also see this expansion of the

357
00:21:08.264 --> 00:21:10.044
S1PR1 positive Tregs.

358
00:21:11.064 --> 00:21:14.264
And with that, I would like to thank the many people who have been involved in

359
00:21:14.304 --> 00:21:18.244
this, and particularly Lily, who I emphasized before, and I am

360
00:21:18.304 --> 00:21:20.384
happy to take any questions.

361
00:21:27.124 --> 00:21:30.344
And just because this is recorded, if people could ask questions at the microphone.

362
00:21:35.104 --> 00:21:37.924
Thank you. My name is Patrick from BMS. Great presentation.

363
00:21:38.584 --> 00:21:40.484
So I think my question

364
00:21:41.324 --> 00:21:44.984
is trying to understand the balance between the expansion of

365
00:21:45.044 --> 00:21:47.964
Tregs and that inflammatory phenotype, which is colitis.

366
00:21:48.534 --> 00:21:51.094
And perhaps the more interesting question is,

367
00:21:52.644 --> 00:21:56.444
do you think that these S1PR positive Tregs have

368
00:21:56.504 --> 00:21:59.624
some sort of inflammatory phenotype that together with the

369
00:21:59.664 --> 00:22:03.384
TH17 just amplifies stuff? Because I would think that if there is an

370
00:22:03.424 --> 00:22:07.264
expansion in the Treg population, in a sense, it should counterbalance

371
00:22:07.284 --> 00:22:09.124
their pro-inflammatory TH17.

372
00:22:09.744 --> 00:22:12.464
Yeah. So I think I'm following this question, but

373
00:22:13.284 --> 00:22:16.944
what I think is happening is that we're getting expansion of Tregs that

374
00:22:17.044 --> 00:22:20.324
are trying to compensate for the

375
00:22:20.364 --> 00:22:22.504
inflammation but are insufficient.

376
00:22:23.044 --> 00:22:26.864
In the CTLA-4 colitis, CTLA-4 is blocked, and

377
00:22:26.924 --> 00:22:30.644
so one of their major mechanisms of control of

378
00:22:30.684 --> 00:22:34.624
inflammation is actually blocked, and so I think that that is

379
00:22:34.664 --> 00:22:38.394
part of what's happening there. PD-1 colitis overall

380
00:22:38.564 --> 00:22:42.164
is less likely to be a sort of out-of-control, rapidly worsening

381
00:22:42.184 --> 00:22:44.744
colitis, and so it's possible that in that

382
00:22:45.544 --> 00:22:49.174
form of colitis, part of the reason why it's not as out of control as CTLA-4

383
00:22:49.304 --> 00:22:51.704
colitis is that those Tregs are having more of a benefit.

384
00:22:51.764 --> 00:22:55.544
And if we were to block CTLA-4 in that moment

385
00:22:55.784 --> 00:22:58.384
in them, we would actually get something that's that much worse.

386
00:22:58.704 --> 00:22:59.584
Okay. Thanks.

387
00:23:04.984 --> 00:23:06.084
Very interesting findings.

388
00:23:07.544 --> 00:23:10.904
Based on the memory cells that are being activated, it's

389
00:23:10.964 --> 00:23:13.144
suggestive that maybe these patients are

390
00:23:14.124 --> 00:23:18.104
right on the cusp of maybe having colitis, but they're being held in check by the

391
00:23:18.144 --> 00:23:21.014
Tregs, and the treatment has then released them.

392
00:23:21.564 --> 00:23:25.544
And if you think that's the case, could this be perhaps

393
00:23:25.564 --> 00:23:29.184
developed as a preclinical diagnostic to maybe exclude some

394
00:23:29.224 --> 00:23:32.304
patients that would be at risk for having this?

395
00:23:33.224 --> 00:23:36.054
So I think it's a really interesting question.

396
00:23:36.204 --> 00:23:40.184
I think the answer is there's something different about the people who

397
00:23:40.404 --> 00:23:41.124
get this colitis,

398
00:23:41.964 --> 00:23:45.124
and I think it's immunologic. We don't know what it is yet.

399
00:23:45.444 --> 00:23:49.104
I'll say that if you get dual checkpoint blockade, you have about a

400
00:23:49.324 --> 00:23:52.664
40% chance of developing colitis at some point in your treatment course.

401
00:23:52.984 --> 00:23:56.344
It's not necessarily going to be the very severe kind, that's sort of 15% to

402
00:23:56.424 --> 00:23:59.744
20%, but a lot of people can get this.

403
00:24:01.124 --> 00:24:04.784
Could a lot of people be right on that cusp of inflammation?

404
00:24:05.204 --> 00:24:09.004
I think yeah, right? I mean, we all have a diverse

405
00:24:09.084 --> 00:24:13.024
microbiome. We constantly are having insults in our gut

406
00:24:13.704 --> 00:24:17.574
that could be causing inflammation, and we're not getting

407
00:24:17.604 --> 00:24:21.564
inflamed. And that may be because these systems work very well, and these are

408
00:24:21.604 --> 00:24:24.594
the core regulatory pathways that do that, and we block them

409
00:24:24.684 --> 00:24:27.296
andThe insult leads to inflammation.

410
00:24:27.596 --> 00:24:30.456
Could we identify those people ahead of time? I think probably.

411
00:24:30.536 --> 00:24:34.516
I think we really have to put more effort into studying people before they start

412
00:24:34.536 --> 00:24:38.416
immunotherapy. And that is a tall order, but I think that's

413
00:24:38.456 --> 00:24:40.696
where the human side of this needs to go.

414
00:24:40.836 --> 00:24:42.006
I think in the mouse models,

415
00:24:43.096 --> 00:24:46.756
to the extent that we could identify things ahead of time in mice and do something

416
00:24:46.796 --> 00:24:48.995
hypothesis-driven, it would work better in people.

417
00:24:49.336 --> 00:24:50.056
Yeah. Thank you.

418
00:24:51.976 --> 00:24:54.356
All right. I think we should move on.

419
00:24:54.576 --> 00:24:58.155
So our next speaker is Dr. Kristen Pauken from MD

420
00:24:58.276 --> 00:24:58.716
Anderson,

421
00:24:59.516 --> 00:25:00.036
and

422
00:25:00.876 --> 00:25:02.976
I'm delighted to hear her talk.

423
00:25:16.196 --> 00:25:17.216
You're a lot taller than me.

424
00:25:18.896 --> 00:25:19.376
Sorry about that.

425
00:25:19.716 --> 00:25:23.476
It's okay. The slides are taking their time.

426
00:25:24.296 --> 00:25:24.636
All right.

427
00:25:25.636 --> 00:25:29.376
So thank you, Michael, for that introduction and a huge thank you for the

428
00:25:29.396 --> 00:25:31.456
invitation to speak at this meeting.

429
00:25:31.876 --> 00:25:35.536
I'm really excited about being part of this session, talking about immune-related

430
00:25:35.576 --> 00:25:38.636
adverse events and the sorts of things that we need to be

431
00:25:39.576 --> 00:25:43.276
thinking about here. And so today, I'm really probably going to talk

432
00:25:43.336 --> 00:25:45.316
about more problems than solutions.

433
00:25:45.696 --> 00:25:49.526
But really, I want to bring light to what I think is this critical issue, and

434
00:25:49.556 --> 00:25:53.276
that's whether or not migratory populations of immune cells or

435
00:25:53.316 --> 00:25:56.936
resident populations of immune cells are really driving checkpoint

436
00:25:56.956 --> 00:25:59.876
inhibitor-induced immune-related adverse events, or IRAEs.

437
00:26:01.256 --> 00:26:02.776
I really have nothing to disclose.

438
00:26:04.096 --> 00:26:08.076
So when we think about the pressing clinical problem that is IRAEs,

439
00:26:08.456 --> 00:26:10.716
there are really three main issues.

440
00:26:10.956 --> 00:26:14.556
First is risk prediction. We know that not all people who

441
00:26:14.576 --> 00:26:18.186
receive immunotherapy for their cancer are going to develop IRAEs,

442
00:26:18.556 --> 00:26:22.126
and so trying to understand the factors that contribute to having higher risk or

443
00:26:22.196 --> 00:26:26.136
lower risk is not trivial. In terms of diagnosis,

444
00:26:26.596 --> 00:26:29.966
we're often relying on patients to be able to identify that they're having

445
00:26:29.976 --> 00:26:33.456
something wrong, and of course, these can happen anywhere in the body, so there's a

446
00:26:33.496 --> 00:26:35.446
lot of symptoms that they have to keep track of.

447
00:26:35.766 --> 00:26:39.476
And then often, we're waiting for referrals to specialists to

448
00:26:39.496 --> 00:26:43.416
follow up and manage. And then with treatment, this is where things get really

449
00:26:43.456 --> 00:26:47.296
tricky because we have to be able to get the toxicity

450
00:26:47.336 --> 00:26:50.616
under control without completely derailing the anti-cancer response.

451
00:26:50.656 --> 00:26:54.456
Because sometimes, we'll get dire to a point where it's like we have to

452
00:26:54.496 --> 00:26:58.336
continue the immunotherapy or the cancer will take the patient, but we also have to

453
00:26:58.376 --> 00:27:01.196
get the toxicity under control or the toxicity will take the patient.

454
00:27:01.756 --> 00:27:04.356
And so often, these are being treated with immunosuppression, which hurts the

455
00:27:04.396 --> 00:27:05.376
anti-tumor response.

456
00:27:07.116 --> 00:27:10.996
So in terms of thinking about the critical research bottlenecks, we think that

457
00:27:11.036 --> 00:27:14.526
research could really advance what we're doing in terms of risk prediction,

458
00:27:14.616 --> 00:27:18.516
diagnosis, and treatment, but there's a lot of things that are holding us back.

459
00:27:18.556 --> 00:27:21.496
The first is variable penetrance of IRAEs.

460
00:27:21.576 --> 00:27:23.616
So as I mentioned, not everybody develops them.

461
00:27:24.236 --> 00:27:25.976
And then there's variable presentation.

462
00:27:26.016 --> 00:27:29.996
And so this has really, I think, been a testament to the complexity of the human

463
00:27:30.076 --> 00:27:33.336
immune system. These can happen literally anywhere in the body.

464
00:27:33.376 --> 00:27:36.496
They can happen early after we start treating. They can happen years later.

465
00:27:36.856 --> 00:27:40.736
They can be mild. They can be life-threatening or even fatal.

466
00:27:40.796 --> 00:27:42.976
They've been really all over the place clinically.

467
00:27:44.196 --> 00:27:47.856
One of the most significant research bottlenecks is actually the inability to

468
00:27:47.976 --> 00:27:50.796
meaningfully sample tissues prior to onset.

469
00:27:51.356 --> 00:27:55.156
So with cancer immunotherapy, for example, we can very easily take a

470
00:27:55.196 --> 00:27:57.156
biopsy of the tumor before we start.

471
00:27:57.216 --> 00:28:00.936
We can call that time zero for our immunotherapy, and we can then sample at

472
00:28:00.976 --> 00:28:03.756
various times after immunotherapy initiation.

473
00:28:03.776 --> 00:28:07.116
But with the toxicities, because we don't know when they're going to happen or

474
00:28:07.156 --> 00:28:11.036
where they're going to happen, getting that pretreatment inflamed tissue sample is

475
00:28:11.236 --> 00:28:14.896
hard, because even within a single tissue, you can have areas

476
00:28:14.936 --> 00:28:17.176
where the toxicity is prevalent and not.

477
00:28:17.196 --> 00:28:20.016
And so knowing that you're sampling the right place is difficult.

478
00:28:21.056 --> 00:28:24.676
Right now, disjointed efforts between studying the relationship of the anti-tumor

479
00:28:24.716 --> 00:28:27.596
response and the toxicity response are challenging.

480
00:28:27.696 --> 00:28:31.556
So these are happening in the same patient, but whether they have anything to

481
00:28:31.596 --> 00:28:35.286
do with each other is unclear. And then, of course, when we treat a patient,

482
00:28:36.176 --> 00:28:39.826
the cancer can respond to the treatment similar

483
00:28:40.056 --> 00:28:42.606
to the toxicity. And so balancing that

484
00:28:44.815 --> 00:28:48.376
dynamic is hard. And then I'm going to argue today that we really need to be

485
00:28:48.446 --> 00:28:51.756
putting the effort into developing mouse models, because I think that the lack of

486
00:28:51.796 --> 00:28:55.726
mouse models to recapitulate the key drivers of pathogenesis in patients is

487
00:28:55.756 --> 00:28:56.756
really holding us back.

488
00:28:58.216 --> 00:29:01.416
So what I want to focus on today is this importance of timing and

489
00:29:01.476 --> 00:29:05.416
location and how we need to understand those two things to be able to better

490
00:29:05.436 --> 00:29:07.236
monitor as well as better treat.

491
00:29:08.576 --> 00:29:12.136
So obviously, we're talking about IRAEs for cancer patients, right?

492
00:29:12.196 --> 00:29:16.106
And so when we first think about the anti-cancer response, many of us really

493
00:29:16.216 --> 00:29:19.796
focus on the tissue microenvironment, the tumor microenvironment itself.

494
00:29:20.176 --> 00:29:24.126
And for good reason. CD8 T cells do the majority of the heavy lifting in terms

495
00:29:24.156 --> 00:29:28.056
of directly killing cancer cells with immunotherapy, and those cells

496
00:29:28.076 --> 00:29:29.576
act in a contact-dependent manner.

497
00:29:29.656 --> 00:29:32.676
So they have to be in the tumor to kill tumor cells.

498
00:29:33.596 --> 00:29:37.576
Similarly, if it's T cells driving your toxicities, those cells have to be

499
00:29:37.656 --> 00:29:40.236
in the inflamed tissue to be causing damage.

500
00:29:40.516 --> 00:29:44.376
This is a little different from B cells, where secretion of their antibodies can

501
00:29:44.456 --> 00:29:47.856
act at a long distance, but for T cells, being in the tissue is

502
00:29:47.896 --> 00:29:48.476
important.

503
00:29:49.336 --> 00:29:52.316
But as you can imagine where I'm going with this based on the picture that I've

504
00:29:52.356 --> 00:29:54.956
shown, this is some Immunology 101.

505
00:29:55.016 --> 00:29:58.716
This is really only the tip of the iceberg. The very tip, right?

506
00:29:59.096 --> 00:30:01.336
These tissues is not where T cell responses start.

507
00:30:01.436 --> 00:30:03.596
These tissues are where T cell responses end.

508
00:30:03.956 --> 00:30:07.916
And so when we think about where T cell responses start, before activation,

509
00:30:07.976 --> 00:30:11.256
naive T cells as well as B cells are completely anatomically

510
00:30:11.336 --> 00:30:15.036
sequestered in spleen, lymph nodes, and blood away from these effector sites.

511
00:30:15.336 --> 00:30:18.816
And they have to first become activated and then migrate to the tissue to

512
00:30:18.916 --> 00:30:20.256
actually do any work.

513
00:30:21.396 --> 00:30:24.516
Similarly, in terms of the innate immune system, there are some cells that seed

514
00:30:24.576 --> 00:30:28.356
tissues early during life, and those are not necessarily constantly replenished.

515
00:30:28.736 --> 00:30:31.796
But for most cells of the immune system, these are constantly being produced in the

516
00:30:31.876 --> 00:30:35.716
bone marrow and exported into blood and then have to get called from blood into

517
00:30:35.756 --> 00:30:39.086
tissue.So when we think about our

518
00:30:39.196 --> 00:30:39.956
patients

519
00:30:40.796 --> 00:30:44.276
defining immunological time zero is extremely

520
00:30:44.316 --> 00:30:47.216
difficult. So in our mice, we know what time zero is.

521
00:30:47.336 --> 00:30:50.516
We have an SPF mouse. We know when we give it a cancer.

522
00:30:50.616 --> 00:30:53.196
We know when we do some sort of immunological perturbation to it.

523
00:30:53.676 --> 00:30:57.356
But in people, we all have this rich and diverse antigen stimulation

524
00:30:57.416 --> 00:30:59.966
history, and we're all our own unique walking case study.

525
00:31:00.386 --> 00:31:03.896
And so with people, we don't know when they come in to receive checkpoint

526
00:31:03.916 --> 00:31:07.556
inhibitors, whether or not they already have these populations in their tissues

527
00:31:07.576 --> 00:31:11.525
because of some antigen stimulation event or if they're new because

528
00:31:11.536 --> 00:31:13.616
we've started giving immunotherapy or both.

529
00:31:13.986 --> 00:31:17.136
And understanding the answer to this question is extremely

530
00:31:17.196 --> 00:31:19.376
important because it impacts how

531
00:31:20.216 --> 00:31:23.736
we monitor, when, where, and how we monitor, also in terms

532
00:31:23.776 --> 00:31:25.036
of how we treat.

533
00:31:25.996 --> 00:31:29.596
So using colitis as an example here, starting with model one, that

534
00:31:29.636 --> 00:31:32.176
tissue-resident leukocytes are driving pathogenesis.

535
00:31:32.256 --> 00:31:36.216
As you can imagine, if your patients come in and they already have these resident

536
00:31:36.256 --> 00:31:40.116
cells in their tissue, then you're going to want to direct your monitoring to

537
00:31:40.176 --> 00:31:43.986
that tissue through biopsy. You're also going to be wanting to focus your

538
00:31:44.056 --> 00:31:47.906
treatments to that tissue. So just to give some definitions, when I talk about

539
00:31:47.936 --> 00:31:51.776
tissue resident T cells, I talk about T cells that had to first become

540
00:31:51.876 --> 00:31:55.066
activated, and then they have to go to that tissue, and then they don't leave that

541
00:31:55.096 --> 00:31:59.056
tissue. They're often associated with markers that are involved in their retention,

542
00:31:59.136 --> 00:32:03.016
things like CD69 and CD103. We love them in cancer and infection

543
00:32:03.056 --> 00:32:06.156
because they seem to work really well in terms of protective capacity.

544
00:32:06.796 --> 00:32:10.416
But obviously in adverse events, this is an issue because if they're highly

545
00:32:10.456 --> 00:32:13.296
functional and stuck there, they're a problem.

546
00:32:13.976 --> 00:32:16.696
I will note the difference between tissue-resident and tissue-resident memory.

547
00:32:17.056 --> 00:32:18.656
Memory means antigen's gone away.

548
00:32:18.996 --> 00:32:22.036
So if antigen hasn't gone away, we typically don't give them the memory

549
00:32:22.496 --> 00:32:23.176
designation.

550
00:32:24.976 --> 00:32:28.696
So Donna Farber's lab has really come a long way in the context of infection in

551
00:32:28.706 --> 00:32:32.176
defining these core transcriptional signatures, which can be really useful for

552
00:32:32.216 --> 00:32:36.126
trying to identify these cells. As you can see here, there's a number

553
00:32:36.156 --> 00:32:39.496
of markers associated with retention and then a lack of markers

554
00:32:39.536 --> 00:32:41.136
associated with exit.

555
00:32:42.936 --> 00:32:46.636
So certainly, if you take a biopsy of inflamed tissue in immune-related

556
00:32:46.696 --> 00:32:50.036
adverse events, we can see signs that there may be resident

557
00:32:50.046 --> 00:32:53.896
populations. So this has been seen in colitis, which

558
00:32:53.956 --> 00:32:57.745
Dr. Dugan recently described. You can also see this in cutaneous

559
00:32:57.745 --> 00:33:00.316
toxicities, myocarditis, neurotoxicities.

560
00:33:00.376 --> 00:33:03.736
Certainly, once you take that sample, you can see those signatures.

561
00:33:05.256 --> 00:33:09.156
The issue, though, is that just because at the time of toxicity you see

562
00:33:09.166 --> 00:33:13.096
those signatures doesn't mean that those cells were necessarily there when you

563
00:33:13.236 --> 00:33:17.066
started. And this is somewhere where I think mouse models are really important

564
00:33:17.336 --> 00:33:19.156
because we can actually kind of suss that out.

565
00:33:19.256 --> 00:33:22.606
We can ask, okay, if you have resident memory cells or you don't, how does that

566
00:33:22.656 --> 00:33:26.636
change things? So why mouse models are important here actually stems from

567
00:33:26.676 --> 00:33:30.436
work from Dave Masopust, who's a leader in this space, and they use this in the

568
00:33:30.476 --> 00:33:33.276
context of acute viral infection to ask about residence.

569
00:33:33.736 --> 00:33:37.516
So they used an approach which we cannot translate to patients, as you'd imagine,

570
00:33:37.856 --> 00:33:41.776
where you surgically conjoin two animals together, and then over one to

571
00:33:41.836 --> 00:33:44.596
two weeks, they will exchange a vasculature between them.

572
00:33:44.916 --> 00:33:47.796
And if the cells are capable of leaving the tissue, you'll find them in the other

573
00:33:47.856 --> 00:33:49.696
animal, and if they can't, then you won't.

574
00:33:50.166 --> 00:33:53.926
And what they found was that in this acute viral infection, the overwhelming

575
00:33:53.976 --> 00:33:57.356
majority of cells in the overwhelming majority of tissues were resident.

576
00:33:58.496 --> 00:34:02.476
What was interesting and why it raises a sign of caution for what we're

577
00:34:02.496 --> 00:34:05.976
doing in humans, when you look at those cells in different tissues, like the

578
00:34:05.996 --> 00:34:09.596
pancreas, the salivary gland, or the female reproductive tract, there's extremely

579
00:34:09.716 --> 00:34:13.596
variable CD69. And importantly, if you look at CD69,

580
00:34:13.636 --> 00:34:17.056
that retention marker, the positive versus negative cells, the

581
00:34:17.076 --> 00:34:20.756
CD69 negative cells in this setting were resident just like the CD69

582
00:34:20.796 --> 00:34:24.616
positive cells. Similarly, CD103 has this same issue.

583
00:34:24.676 --> 00:34:28.647
It tends to be a better marker for residents in epithelial layers and

584
00:34:28.716 --> 00:34:30.976
less effective in lamina propria.

585
00:34:32.377 --> 00:34:36.286
Adding another wrinkle to interpreting our single-cell RNA-seq data sets,

586
00:34:36.656 --> 00:34:40.357
work from, again, the Masopust lab as well as John Wherry's lab and Laura McKay's

587
00:34:40.417 --> 00:34:44.276
lab, have shown that exhausted cells can actually have a lot of transcriptional

588
00:34:44.397 --> 00:34:47.156
overlap with bona fide tissue-resident memory cells.

589
00:34:47.176 --> 00:34:50.966
And it seems like a lot of the same transcriptional machinery that helps resident

590
00:34:51.016 --> 00:34:54.647
memory cells stay in tissues also helps exhausted cells stay in

591
00:34:54.656 --> 00:34:57.256
tissues. And so this kind of complicates the picture

592
00:34:57.296 --> 00:35:01.216
here. So when we think about tissue-resident populations, we

593
00:35:01.276 --> 00:35:05.156
know that when we take biopsies of inflamed lesional tissues from these

594
00:35:05.176 --> 00:35:08.036
patients, we see these resident-like cells.

595
00:35:08.076 --> 00:35:12.026
Whether or not those are actually there when we start treatment, we don't know, and

596
00:35:12.076 --> 00:35:14.176
that lack of the ability to do the pre-treatment

597
00:35:14.196 --> 00:35:18.116
assessment is really challenging for

598
00:35:18.196 --> 00:35:18.416
us.

599
00:35:19.826 --> 00:35:22.996
So that brings me to the other half of the coin, and these don't necessarily have

600
00:35:23.056 --> 00:35:25.376
to be mutually exclusive in a person, right?

601
00:35:25.416 --> 00:35:27.296
These can both be happening at the same time.

602
00:35:27.326 --> 00:35:29.576
We just need to understand the contribution of each.

603
00:35:29.996 --> 00:35:33.796
So the other side of things is migration, and again, using the colitis

604
00:35:33.856 --> 00:35:37.776
example because the colon is a place that has unique trafficking

605
00:35:37.836 --> 00:35:41.456
receptors to get cells in, which is really, really, really helpful here.

606
00:35:41.536 --> 00:35:45.306
So you can imagine if migration is critical for inducing colitis, then

607
00:35:45.396 --> 00:35:49.316
blocking migration would help. And fortunately, there's inhibitors of the

608
00:35:49.336 --> 00:35:53.076
integrin alpha 4 beta 7, which are clinically approved and regularly used in

609
00:35:53.096 --> 00:35:55.416
colitis and have had a lot of success there.

610
00:35:55.436 --> 00:35:58.676
So if you can block that migration and you have success, that's great.

611
00:35:58.996 --> 00:36:01.896
But if the cells are already in the tissue, then blocking migration is not going to

612
00:36:01.936 --> 00:36:02.496
be helpful.

613
00:36:03.816 --> 00:36:07.796
So I want to really talk about how we measure migration and why it's important that

614
00:36:07.816 --> 00:36:09.576
we develop animal studies to do this.

615
00:36:10.576 --> 00:36:14.286
So this has been a major research bottleneck both in people as well as in mice, and

616
00:36:14.316 --> 00:36:17.356
the reason for that, I've mentioned that cells have to go from the blood into

617
00:36:17.416 --> 00:36:21.246
tissues. We know that they have intrinsic differences in their entry rates across

618
00:36:21.276 --> 00:36:25.216
different leukocyte subsets. But as soon as it passes from the blood into tissue,

619
00:36:25.596 --> 00:36:29.516
we have no idea how long it's been there, whether it's been a minute, an hour,

620
00:36:29.656 --> 00:36:32.996
a week, a month. And for both cells of the adaptive immune system and the innate

621
00:36:33.036 --> 00:36:36.376
immune system, we think that the time in the tissue really shapes their

622
00:36:36.916 --> 00:36:39.416
phenotype and function. We know cells adapt in tissues.

623
00:36:39.716 --> 00:36:43.576
And in the context of chronic antigen, this can really shape the functional output

624
00:36:43.616 --> 00:36:47.484
of these cells.So as I mentioned before, in the context of residence,

625
00:36:47.564 --> 00:36:51.164
parabiosis has been helpful here for asking if cells are capable of leaving

626
00:36:51.524 --> 00:36:55.124
but because it takes so long for these blood vessels to form, it's not as useful

627
00:36:55.164 --> 00:36:56.904
for studying acute migration events

628
00:36:57.824 --> 00:36:59.544
Photoactivatable dyes are useful.

629
00:36:59.604 --> 00:37:03.074
These are encoded in the germline, and you can shine light on external tissues, and

630
00:37:03.104 --> 00:37:06.304
those cells will change colors. And while that's great, this has been

631
00:37:06.864 --> 00:37:09.984
limited for the toxicity field because it requires extensive breeding.

632
00:37:10.064 --> 00:37:11.984
Often, our mouse models are not on this background.

633
00:37:12.384 --> 00:37:15.884
It's also really best for labeling external tissues, so it limits where we can use

634
00:37:15.944 --> 00:37:16.124
it.

635
00:37:17.503 --> 00:37:20.724
So fortunately for me, this is something that my long-term collaborator, Jason

636
00:37:20.784 --> 00:37:24.384
Schinkel, was trying to solve for his own work, and he developed a timestamping

637
00:37:24.444 --> 00:37:28.004
approach that I really want to highlight to allow us to actually track migration

638
00:37:28.044 --> 00:37:31.924
from the blood into tissues. He has published a couple of papers on this at

639
00:37:31.964 --> 00:37:34.084
this point if you're interested in checking out the method.

640
00:37:35.204 --> 00:37:38.414
This is an adaptation over a technique that's been used for over 20 years in the

641
00:37:38.504 --> 00:37:42.404
field. Again, Dave Masopust's lab has published a protocols paper on this.

642
00:37:42.764 --> 00:37:46.184
Basically, you inject a fluorescently labeled antibody into the

643
00:37:46.204 --> 00:37:49.894
vasculature three to five minutes before euthanizing the mouse, and you can see if

644
00:37:49.924 --> 00:37:52.744
the cell's binding the antibody, they're actually in the blood and not the tissue

645
00:37:52.804 --> 00:37:55.624
parenchyma. But if they're in the parenchyma, then they're IV-negative.

646
00:37:57.184 --> 00:38:00.444
So we were interested in whether or not we could leverage this concept to track

647
00:38:00.484 --> 00:38:04.344
migration into tissues since leukocytes have to traffic from the

648
00:38:04.384 --> 00:38:07.704
blood into the tissue. And we knew that to do this, we needed

649
00:38:07.884 --> 00:38:11.014
antibodies that would not cause deletion of the cells, would not themselves get

650
00:38:11.044 --> 00:38:13.704
internalized and degraded, and would not leak into tissues.

651
00:38:14.344 --> 00:38:17.844
And so we tested a whole panel of antibodies, giving CTV or

652
00:38:17.884 --> 00:38:21.664
CFSE-labeled cells, so we could identify the cells independently of the antibody

653
00:38:21.704 --> 00:38:23.344
and then harvested mice 10 minutes later.

654
00:38:23.764 --> 00:38:27.104
And what we found was that certain antibodies that are known to really effectively

655
00:38:27.124 --> 00:38:30.364
deplete cells do. Thy1.1 killed all the cells in 10 minutes.

656
00:38:30.724 --> 00:38:34.104
CD8 and CD4 are well on their way. But CD45.2 and

657
00:38:34.144 --> 00:38:37.464
CD45 did not. So it's like, great, you've gone from 3 minutes to 10 minutes.

658
00:38:37.664 --> 00:38:40.944
How impressive is that, right? Well, we first looked at

659
00:38:40.984 --> 00:38:43.484
CD45.2 and tried to elongate this.

660
00:38:43.514 --> 00:38:47.374
And so what we found was that at 10 minutes, 24 hours, and 72 hours, we could

661
00:38:47.444 --> 00:38:51.284
still very easily distinguish these cells from a no-injection control.

662
00:38:52.464 --> 00:38:56.184
Kind of a word of caution here. When we compared CD45.2 to

663
00:38:56.244 --> 00:39:00.084
the pan-CD45 epitope 30F11, you

664
00:39:00.124 --> 00:39:04.084
can see that with the 104 clone, you get very little loss of

665
00:39:04.144 --> 00:39:07.433
signal in that 10 minutes to 24 hours period, whereas with the

666
00:39:07.444 --> 00:39:11.414
CD45 30F11 clone, we lose a lot of that signal in

667
00:39:11.424 --> 00:39:15.294
the 24 hour period. And if we try to actually count the cells that we get

668
00:39:15.384 --> 00:39:17.424
back, we actually lose a lot of the cells as well.

669
00:39:17.504 --> 00:39:18.974
So if you're going to use this for your own work,

670
00:39:19.804 --> 00:39:21.544
we certainly recommend the clone 104.

671
00:39:22.674 --> 00:39:26.384
What I'm not showing is that at the concentrations that we're giving into an intact

672
00:39:26.444 --> 00:39:30.344
CD45.2 mouse, we don't see any evidence of leakage into tissues.

673
00:39:30.384 --> 00:39:33.814
This is also not saturating, so you can actually use the same clone over and over

674
00:39:33.824 --> 00:39:37.534
again in different colors to create these temporal maps of how immune cells are

675
00:39:37.564 --> 00:39:38.724
trafficking into tissues.

676
00:39:39.924 --> 00:39:43.244
So my lab has been using this in the context of checkpoint immunotherapy to study

677
00:39:43.364 --> 00:39:47.304
both the protective anti-cancer side as well as the pathogenic adverse

678
00:39:47.344 --> 00:39:50.644
event side. These are the people who have been leading those projects.

679
00:39:51.204 --> 00:39:54.984
And what we can do, if you have a CD45.2 expressing preclinical

680
00:39:55.064 --> 00:39:58.584
model, you just do your normal experimental setup, and then you can start

681
00:39:58.644 --> 00:40:02.304
injecting these antibodies. Like I said, within 72 hours of harvest,

682
00:40:02.624 --> 00:40:05.664
we always include a three-minute control to exclude what's actively in the

683
00:40:05.684 --> 00:40:06.324
vasculature.

684
00:40:07.524 --> 00:40:11.204
So this is what a tumor looks like. We're at AACR. This is a cancer conference.

685
00:40:11.564 --> 00:40:15.344
We always see in every tumor type that we look at, there's always a population of

686
00:40:15.364 --> 00:40:17.284
cells actively in the blood. We kick those out.

687
00:40:17.684 --> 00:40:20.204
We see a large population that is IV-negative.

688
00:40:20.264 --> 00:40:22.984
Those are presumably the cells that have been in the tumor for longer than 24

689
00:40:23.044 --> 00:40:26.864
hours. And then we have these 24-hour positive, three-minute negative that were

690
00:40:26.904 --> 00:40:29.744
in the blood at that snapshot in time at 24 hours.

691
00:40:29.764 --> 00:40:33.744
The label is actually a short labeling window and now is in the tumor.

692
00:40:34.884 --> 00:40:38.464
So in terms of some controls, an uninjected control obviously is the ideal control.

693
00:40:38.854 --> 00:40:41.784
But some other natural positives and negatives, the tumor-draining lymph node

694
00:40:41.824 --> 00:40:45.104
always has very few three-minute positive cells, and the peripheral blood always

695
00:40:45.144 --> 00:40:47.644
has a lot of three-minute positive cells.

696
00:40:49.144 --> 00:40:51.844
This is what this looks like in other types of tissues.

697
00:40:51.884 --> 00:40:54.824
So as I mentioned, my lab is using this in pathogenic immune responses.

698
00:40:54.884 --> 00:40:58.584
This is the pancreas in an autoimmune prone NOD

699
00:40:58.644 --> 00:41:01.284
mouse, and then cardiac tissue in a myocarditis-prone mouse.

700
00:41:01.624 --> 00:41:05.544
We also have kidney and salivary gland shown from a mouse

701
00:41:05.564 --> 00:41:09.264
that just has an MC38 tumor. No, it has a melanoma tumor. Excuse me.

702
00:41:09.884 --> 00:41:13.624
And that is at homeostasis. You can see each of these different tissues has a

703
00:41:13.664 --> 00:41:17.364
different three-minute versus 24-hour IV antibody profile.

704
00:41:17.384 --> 00:41:20.614
What's cool is that when you perturb the immune system, the immune system responds.

705
00:41:20.954 --> 00:41:23.344
And a lot of that response involves migration.

706
00:41:23.384 --> 00:41:27.044
And so you can see this is the salivary gland in a mouse that got a

707
00:41:27.104 --> 00:41:31.004
cancer vaccine. Suddenly, the 24-hour IV positive by three-minute

708
00:41:31.044 --> 00:41:32.564
IV positive distribution changes.

709
00:41:34.064 --> 00:41:37.244
So one of my postdocs in the lab, Ariel Desens, has been looking at this in the

