1445
01:22:33.484 --> 01:22:35.484
We have looked at it. Because they're not

1446
01:22:36.824 --> 01:22:37.373
published

1447
01:22:38.824 --> 01:22:40.404
antibodies, these patients are on trials.

1448
01:22:40.664 --> 01:22:44.534
I can't show any of the data from that, but they are

1449
01:22:44.604 --> 01:22:47.124
used. There is one antibody,

1450
01:22:47.664 --> 01:22:50.964
tremelimumab, that has reduced Fc

1451
01:22:51.604 --> 01:22:55.464
gamma receptor function, and there's questions

1452
01:22:55.504 --> 01:22:57.884
about how active it is compared to ipilimumab.

1453
01:22:58.164 --> 01:23:01.634
It is hard to tease that out because they haven't been directly compared,

1454
01:23:02.044 --> 01:23:05.904
but that's led multiple companies to go towards the Fc enhancement.

1455
01:23:06.504 --> 01:23:10.044
I bet that it's dependent on the specific system, though.

1456
01:23:10.384 --> 01:23:13.604
I think your data's very clear. In some

1457
01:23:13.964 --> 01:23:14.474
models,

1458
01:23:15.324 --> 01:23:18.784
if you just block CTLA-4, you get really good anti-tumor

1459
01:23:18.844 --> 01:23:22.804
responses. And I'm sure that is the case in humans for

1460
01:23:22.824 --> 01:23:25.584
some kinds of cancer, and maybe not all of them.

1461
01:23:25.624 --> 01:23:29.324
But if we can figure out which ones are which, it could

1462
01:23:29.384 --> 01:23:33.324
allow us to separate toxicity, at least in some settings, from

1463
01:23:34.284 --> 01:23:34.763
response.

1464
01:23:38.484 --> 01:23:41.784
Also say that there are experiments ongoing blocking

1465
01:23:42.864 --> 01:23:46.784
the S1P1R receptor in humans. So we

1466
01:23:46.804 --> 01:23:48.984
will see if that makes things worse.

1467
01:23:49.924 --> 01:23:51.464
I was going to ask you about the

1468
01:23:52.604 --> 01:23:55.964
S1PR1 receptor, because isn't it normally involved in

1469
01:23:56.044 --> 01:23:56.624
egress?

1470
01:23:57.264 --> 01:24:01.184
From the lymph node. And so we think they're coming out

1471
01:24:01.224 --> 01:24:03.084
of the lymph node and then getting back into the-

1472
01:24:03.094 --> 01:24:04.704
And they just haven't down-regulated it yet.

1473
01:24:04.804 --> 01:24:08.644
Yeah. We think they're new. If we could do that in people,

1474
01:24:08.704 --> 01:24:10.144
which would be very hard. But

1475
01:24:10.304 --> 01:24:14.284
my hypothesis would be

1476
01:24:14.324 --> 01:24:17.064
that they are new immigrants into the

1477
01:24:18.004 --> 01:24:18.284
colon.

1478
01:24:18.484 --> 01:24:19.384
Very interesting.

1479
01:24:19.424 --> 01:24:22.464
But obviously, it's very hard to know that.

1480
01:24:22.494 --> 01:24:26.224
And we're looking very early on in the response.

1481
01:24:26.264 --> 01:24:30.064
Part of what we've been trying to do is

1482
01:24:30.124 --> 01:24:33.944
avoid looking at downstream consequences

1483
01:24:34.064 --> 01:24:38.054
of mucosal disruption. Because I think that then you get to final

1484
01:24:38.104 --> 01:24:42.094
common pathways of innate inflammatory responses, and

1485
01:24:42.104 --> 01:24:44.884
it's no longer telling you what's starting this.

1486
01:24:44.924 --> 01:24:48.624
If you strip the mucosa off, all forms of colitis start to look the same.

1487
01:24:49.104 --> 01:24:50.124
Yeah. I do think that the

1488
01:24:51.004 --> 01:24:54.534
sampling as early as possible to get at the drivers instead of the

1489
01:24:54.604 --> 01:24:58.544
consequences is really critical, and certainly can be challenging for

1490
01:24:58.584 --> 01:25:02.474
adverse events because they have to identify that there's a problem and

1491
01:25:02.484 --> 01:25:05.464
then get in, and then you have to mobilize the tissue collection team.

1492
01:25:06.144 --> 01:25:09.804
But it's really important, I think, to be able to study what's happening.

1493
01:25:09.884 --> 01:25:13.464
I think it's also important that the people taking biopsies

1494
01:25:13.504 --> 01:25:14.924
understand what the purpose of it is.

1495
01:25:15.144 --> 01:25:18.724
So, for our experiments, we really target

1496
01:25:18.784 --> 01:25:22.624
adjacent normal appearing tissue rather than sort of

1497
01:25:22.664 --> 01:25:24.624
the most diseased looking tissue.

1498
01:25:24.644 --> 01:25:28.284
And that's, again, because we're trying to look at the early responses

1499
01:25:28.424 --> 01:25:32.336
rather than... what happens when the

1500
01:25:32.356 --> 01:25:34.176
mucosa actually starts to fall apart.

1501
01:25:34.356 --> 01:25:34.856
Yeah.

1502
01:25:38.196 --> 01:25:41.836
Questions from the audience. There are a few more of them online.

1503
01:25:48.836 --> 01:25:51.876
One of the questions that's in here is about,

1504
01:25:54.236 --> 01:25:57.496
when are Tregs depleted? When are they expanded?

1505
01:25:57.976 --> 01:25:58.436
And

1506
01:25:59.436 --> 01:26:02.556
the question is, "I'm confused." And I think

1507
01:26:02.636 --> 01:26:03.696
that's the

1508
01:26:04.736 --> 01:26:07.856
situation in the field right now, and we still don't have a clear answer.

1509
01:26:07.986 --> 01:26:10.976
And I think that's why it's so important to

1510
01:26:11.156 --> 01:26:15.076
have animal models where we can ask lots

1511
01:26:15.116 --> 01:26:19.016
of different kinds of questions and really be able to say, "These

1512
01:26:19.056 --> 01:26:20.976
are the situations when depletion happens.

1513
01:26:21.036 --> 01:26:24.846
This is what occurs when there's depletion." So that we can then

1514
01:26:24.856 --> 01:26:28.566
compare that to what we see in patients and

1515
01:26:28.596 --> 01:26:32.456
form hypotheses, either that we can test in trials or at least as ways of

1516
01:26:32.496 --> 01:26:36.266
understanding the human data. Without a mouse model, it becomes

1517
01:26:36.776 --> 01:26:39.936
much, much harder to test hypotheses.

1518
01:26:40.156 --> 01:26:43.946
And so, that's what I think is so exciting about

1519
01:26:43.946 --> 01:26:47.796
this model here, is that it allows us to start to address those questions.

1520
01:26:47.856 --> 01:26:50.676
We do not have a clear answer about what's happening in people.

1521
01:26:50.756 --> 01:26:54.496
I think in some

1522
01:26:54.536 --> 01:26:58.156
settings, it's clear that we get expansion

1523
01:26:58.216 --> 01:27:01.476
of Treg populations. Are they functional?

1524
01:27:01.796 --> 01:27:04.656
What are those functions? It's still an open question.

1525
01:27:05.416 --> 01:27:09.196
Well, and I do think if you do have an animal model, if you're using a

1526
01:27:09.296 --> 01:27:12.416
CTLA-4 inhibitor, it's really important to look.

1527
01:27:12.546 --> 01:27:12.616
Yeah.

1528
01:27:12.636 --> 01:27:15.936
To actually look and measure, is your clone of

1529
01:27:15.976 --> 01:27:19.636
CTLA-4 deleting your Tregs in your tissues of

1530
01:27:19.696 --> 01:27:20.596
interest? Because

1531
01:27:21.516 --> 01:27:25.106
there are reports from the literature of like, clone X is depleting, clone Y is

1532
01:27:25.116 --> 01:27:27.996
depleting, and then there's other reports that like, no, they don't.

1533
01:27:28.516 --> 01:27:32.456
And I do think there's a lot of tissue dependence in terms of whether or not you'll

1534
01:27:32.516 --> 01:27:36.176
actually get deletion. And so checking is really

1535
01:27:36.196 --> 01:27:39.496
important. Don't just assume that you will because somebody else published that you

1536
01:27:39.536 --> 01:27:42.836
will, or assume that you won't because somebody else published that you won't.

1537
01:27:43.576 --> 01:27:47.456
Yeah, but the problem is the definition of peripheral Tregs.

1538
01:27:47.536 --> 01:27:51.396
If you look in our testing, you look at FoxP3, there's no depletion because you

1539
01:27:51.416 --> 01:27:51.996
don't see them,

1540
01:27:53.256 --> 01:27:55.836
because that's so broad, the definition.

1541
01:27:56.176 --> 01:27:59.756
And in many human studies, they only look FoxP3 CD4 positive.

1542
01:27:59.856 --> 01:28:03.836
That's the only thing they look at. By doing that, basically you can't even look.

1543
01:28:05.256 --> 01:28:08.916
So what is very interesting, when we look at that data that you were

1544
01:28:08.956 --> 01:28:12.316
analyzing, we saw a depletion of peripheral

1545
01:28:12.356 --> 01:28:15.816
Tregs according to our definition of peripheral Tregs.

1546
01:28:16.596 --> 01:28:19.056
But we were not 100% sure those are

1547
01:28:20.096 --> 01:28:22.316
real peripheral. But we could find

1548
01:28:23.616 --> 01:28:27.416
a gene signature that appears to be peripheral

1549
01:28:27.436 --> 01:28:31.116
Tregs and were depleted in the human samples with a CTLA-4

1550
01:28:31.196 --> 01:28:35.066
antibody. But we were not totally happy with it because there was no

1551
01:28:35.396 --> 01:28:38.596
clear-cut definition. This is our definition that

1552
01:28:38.656 --> 01:28:41.256
we-- We basically

1553
01:28:42.296 --> 01:28:45.776
made up the definition, but if that is a correct definition, I

1554
01:28:46.116 --> 01:28:48.516
cannot tell you. But we saw the depletion.

1555
01:28:49.016 --> 01:28:49.136
Right.

1556
01:28:49.416 --> 01:28:52.896
But maybe they truly are the ones.

1557
01:28:54.096 --> 01:28:55.316
I just don't know for sure.

1558
01:28:55.846 --> 01:28:56.616
So, we

1559
01:28:57.716 --> 01:29:01.696
took your definition, reanalyzed our data, and we saw exactly the

1560
01:29:01.756 --> 01:29:02.276
same thing.

1561
01:29:03.696 --> 01:29:07.036
That's why we added all of the extra samples to start to see, okay, well, what

1562
01:29:07.076 --> 01:29:10.816
happens when we go from 24 patients to a few dozen?

1563
01:29:11.816 --> 01:29:14.636
And I think that does help with humans.

1564
01:29:14.656 --> 01:29:17.716
You add more and more data, you start to see new things.

1565
01:29:18.536 --> 01:29:21.946
And we're still in the analysis phase of this, so this is-- I mean, it's

1566
01:29:22.396 --> 01:29:26.096
early data and we hope to have more to say in the next few months.

1567
01:29:27.636 --> 01:29:31.156
I think that we are out of time, but thank you all for your

1568
01:29:31.176 --> 01:29:35.016
attention. And again, I want to thank both of the other speakers

1569
01:29:35.256 --> 01:29:38.756
for agreeing to come today. Your talks were fantastic, and I really appreciate it.

1570
01:29:39.436 --> 01:29:40.216
Thank you, everyone.

